etymologies: late 15th century; earliest use found in Craft of Dying. From post-classical Latin praesentialis present (9th century; frequently from 11th century in British sources; attested earlier as a variant reading for praesentalis present) from classical Latin praesentia + -ālis

definitions: Of or relating to presence; having or implying actual presence with a person or in a place; present.
Relating or having reference to the present tense.
